rial; \"| '''[[Brownlow Medal]] votes'''\n|-\n! style=\"width:50%;\"| Season\n! style=\"width:50%;\"| Votes\n|-\n| [[1995 Brownlow Medal|1995]]\n| 0\n|-\n| [[1996 Brownlow Medal|1996]]\n| 3\n|-\n| [[1997 Brownlow Medal|1997]]\n| 7\n|-\n| [[1998 Brownlow Medal|1998]]\n| 5\n|-\n| [[1999 Brownlow Medal|1999]]\n| 9\n|-\n| [[2000 Brownlow Medal|2000]]\n| 14\n|-\n| [[2001 Brownlow Medal|2001]]\n| 15\n|-\n| [[2002 Brownlow Medal|2002]]\n| 6\n|-\n| [[2003 Brownlow Medal|2003]]\n| 14\n|-\n| [[2004 Brownlow Medal|2004]]\n| 10\n|-\n| [[2005 Brownlow Medal|2005]]\n| 3\n|-\n| [[2006 Brownlow Medal|2006]]\n| 3\n|-\n| [[2007 Brownlow Medal|2007]]\n| 0\n|-\n| [[2008 Brownlow Medal|2008]]\n| 5\n|-\n| [[2009 Brownlow Medal|2009]]\n| 3\n|-\n| '''Total'''\n| '''97'''\n|}\n\n*'''Team'''\n**'''[[AFL Premiership]] ([[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]])''': 2000\n**'''[[McClelland Trophy]] ([[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]])''': 1999, 2000, 2001\n**'''[[Australian Football League pre-season competition|Pre-Season Cup]] ([[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]])''': 2000\n*'''Individual'''\n**'''[[Coleman Medal]]''': 2000, 2001, 2003\n**'''[[All-Australian team|All-Australian]]''': 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003\n**'''[[List of Essendon Football Club leading goalkickers|Essendon F.C. Leading Goalkicker]]''': 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2007, 2008, 2009\n**'''[[List of Essendon Football Club captains|Essendon F.C. Captain]]''': 2006-2009\n**'''[[Australian international rules football team|Australian Representative Honours in]] [[International rules football|International Rules Football]]''': 2001\n**'''[[International Rules Series#Jim Stynes Medal|Jim Stynes Medal]]''': 2001\n**'''[[Goal of the Year (AFL)|Goal of the Year]]''': 2007\n**'''[[Mark of the Year|Alex Jesaulenko Medal - Mark of the Year]]''': 2008\n**'''[[AFL Rising Star|AFL Rising Star Nominee]]''': 1996 (Round 19)\n**'''[[Essendon Football Club#Champions of Essendon|Champions of Essendon - No. 22]]'''\n**'''[[Australian Football Hall of Fame]] inductee'''\n\n==Retirement==\nOn 23 September 2009, Lloyd announced his retirement to a packed media conference at the Essendon Football Club Hall of Fame. Although he had been offered another contract,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=7035 |title=Lloyd requests more time |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923004305/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=7035 |archive-date=23 September 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Lloyd said that \"now is my time from a physical and mental point of view\" and that he would \"...prefer to go a year too early than a year too late.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/newsarticle/tabid/208/newsid/85180/default.aspx |title=Lloyd quits |publisher=Afl.com.au |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nTo celebrate Lloyd's career, the Coventry End of [[Docklands Stadium]] is renamed the Lloyd End for Essendon home games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/honour-a-fitting-end-for-matthew-lloyd/story-e6frf9jf-1225809744183 |title=Honour a fitting end for Matthew Lloyd |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lloyd was appointed assistant coach at the AIS-AFL Academy<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ausport.gov.au/ais/sports/australian_football/news/afl_stars_lloyd_and_oloughlin_lend_support_to_emerging_talent |title=Lloyd and O'Loughlin Lend Support To Emerging Talent |publisher=Ausport.gov.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110330165928/http://www.ausport.gov.au/ais/sports/australian_football/news/afl_stars_lloyd_and_oloughlin_lend_support_to_emerging_talent |archive-date=30 March 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> however he ruled out applying for an AFL coaching position.<ref>http://www.theadvocate.com.au/news/local/sport/football-australian-rules/lloyds-coaching-aspirations-on-hold/2370200.aspx</ref>\n\n==Media work==\nLloyd co-hosted children's AFL show ''Auskick'n Around'' on [[Fox Footy Channel]] with [[Brad Johnson (Australian footballer)|Brad Johnson]] from the [[Western Bulldogs]] from 2003 until it was cancelled at the end of 2005.\n\nIn 2006 Lloyd had a weekly spot as a panelist on [[Fox Footy]]'s ''White Line Fever'' and after being forced to spend extended time off the field because of injury, he became recognised for his informative views on all things football \u2013 his roles included being a [[special comments]] commentator on [[Triple M]]'s football coverage as well as more regular appearances on ''[[The AFL Footy Show]]'', as a panelist.\n\nIn 2009 Lloyd appeared as a regular panelist on a new show, ''[[One Week at a Time (AFL)|One Week at a Time]]'', as well as doing special comments on [[Network Ten]] and writing a regular column for  ''[[The Age]]'' newspaper. Following his retirement Lloyd has been heavily involved in the media.\n\nLloyd signed with the Network Ten<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onehd.com.au/shows-matthew-lloyd.htm| title = OneHD: Matthew Lloyd profile| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110723224346/http://one.com.au/shows-matthew-lloyd.htm | archivedate=23 July 2011}}</ref> AFL team as an expert commentator for the [[2010 AFL season|2010]] and 2011 AFL seasons on Channel Ten and [[10 Bold|One HD]] (he had already provided special commentary during various matches of the [[2009 AFL season]] for the network), until [[Ten Sport]] lost the rights at the end of the [[2011 AFL season]]. He also worked for radio station [[SEN 1116|SEN]], was a co-host of ''[[The Game Plan (Australian TV series)|The Game Plan]]'' on One HD during 2011 and continued working for ''The Age''.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/afl/by/matthew-lloyd The Age: Matthew Lloyd]</ref>\n\nLloyd's autobiography (co-authored with Andrew Clarke), ''Straight Shooter'', was released in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/matthew-lloyds-final-stand-for-the-bombers/story-e6frf9jf-1226098631937 |title=Lloyd's Final Stand For The Bombers |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/a-fear-of-failure-was-my-greatest-spur-from-the-very-start-20110720-1howe.html |title=A fear of failure was my greatest spur from the very start |publisher=Theage.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nAfter Network Ten lost the AFL broadcasting rights, Lloyd joined the [[Nine Network]] for 2012 to be a panelist on ''[[The Footy Show (AFL)|The Footy Show]]'' and ''[[The Footy Show (AFL)|The Sunday Footy Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/tv-radio/channel-9-signs-matthew-lloyd/story-e6frf9ho-1226171130199 |title=Channel 9 signs Matthew Lloyd |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> He also left SEN to join [[3AW]]'s AFL special comments team.\n\nIn 2013, he joined ''[[Footy Classified]]'' as a panelist alongside [[Gary Lyon]], [[Craig Hutchison (broadcaster)|Craig Hutchison]] and [[Caroline Wilson]]; as well as continuing his regular roles on ''The Sunday Footy Show'' and 3AW Football. Lloyd is also a recurring panelist on ''The Footy Show'' and on occasion appears on ''[[Nine News Melbourne]]'' to provide insights into the weekly round of matches.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=9NewsMelb |number=1045595844425072641 |date=28 September 2018 |title=Tomorrow's Grand Final tips with @MatthewLloyd18. Who will win? #9News }}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nOn 14 November 2014 it was announced that Lloyd would return to the Essendon Football Club as a part-time forwards coach, working closely with the club's forwards.<ref>[http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/2014-11-14/lloyd-back-in Lloyd Back In for 2015], Essendon Football Club official website, 14 November 2014</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLloyd's parents are [[John Lloyd (Australian footballer)|John]] and Bev Lloyd. John Lloyd played 29 games for [[Carlton Football Club|Carlton]] from 1965\u20131967 and coached the Braybrook Football Club to three premierships. The family moved to Scotland for three years because of John Lloyd's work and it was there that Lloyd played [[rugby football|rugby]] and [[soccer]] for his [[Currie]] club.\n\nLloyd has two older brothers, Simon, who is an assistant coach at the [[Geelong Football Club]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fremantlefc.com.au/news/newsarticle/tabid/7009/newsid/104367/default.aspx |title=Assistant coaching role for Simon Lloyd |publisher=Fremantlefc.com.au |date=2010-10-22 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302075336/http://www.fremantlefc.com.au/news/newsarticle/tabid/7009/newsid/104367/default.aspx |archive-date=2 March 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Brad Lloyd|Brad]], who is  a former [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]] player (and former captain of the [[Williamstown Football Club]]) and now head of football at the [[Carlton Football Club]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fremantlefc.com.au/Default.aspx?tabid=7009&newsId=55446 |title=National Recruiting Manager appointed |publisher=Fremantlefc.com.au |date=2008-02-20 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706104827/http://www.fremantlefc.com.au/Default.aspx?tabid=7009&newsId=55446 |archivedate=6 July 2011 }}</ref> as well as one older sister, Kylie, who is the Unit Manager at ''[[The AFL Footy Show|The Footy Show]]''.\n\nOn 9 November 2002, Lloyd married his childhood sweetheart, Lisa-Marie Caparello, usually known as \"Lisa\", at [[Xavier College (Melbourne)|Xavier College]] Chapel. Their wedding was covered by ''New Idea'' magazine and a documentary of the day, titled ''One Day In November'', was also aired on [[Fox Footy]] Channel. \nLisa Lloyd appeared on [[The Footy Show (AFL)|The Footy Show]]'s singing competition, ''Screamers'', in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4209 |title=Support our latest Bomber star |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date=2005-04-28 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050619023559/http://essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4209 |archive-date=19 June 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and was also a regular presenter on [[Fox Footy]]'s ''Living With Footballers''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/03/31/1080544543170.html |title=Living With Footballers |publisher=The Age |date=2004-04-01 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Lloyds have three children; Jaeda Ruby (born December 2006),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4978 |title=Lloyd Family Grows By One |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date=2006-12-16 |accessdate=2012-09-25 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Kira Grace (born September 2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/another-baby-girl-for-lloyd/story-e6frf7jo-1225769757156 |title=Another baby girl for Lloyd |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> and Jacob Matthew (born November 2012).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/a/Lloyd-family-welcomes-baby-boy/10227 |title=Lloyd family welcomes baby boy |publisher=Essendon footy Club |date= |accessdate=2012-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130214636/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/a/Lloyd-family-welcomes-baby-boy/10227 |archive-date=30 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book| first=Matthew |last=Lloyd | year=2011 |publisher=Random House Australia |isbn= 978-1-86471-293-3 |title=Matthew Lloyd: Straight Shooter}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Essplayer|ref=13223}}\n*{{AFL Tables|ref=M/Matthew_Lloyd0.html}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110226171645/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/team/player-past.asp?id=542#profile Essendon Past Players Profile: Matthew Lloyd]\n\n{{AFL Coleman Medallists}}\n{{2000 Essendon premiership players}}\n{{Essendon Football Club captains}}\n{{Essendon leading goalkickers}}\n{{1998 All-Australian team}}\n{{1999 All-Australian team}}\n{{2000 All-Australian team}}\n{{2001 All-Australian team}}\n{{2003 All-Australian team}}\n{{Alex Jesaulenko Medal}}\n{{Goal of the Year}}\n{{1996 AFL Rising Star nominees}}\n{{Jim Stynes Medal}}\n{{1998 Australian international rules team}}\n{{2001 Australian international rules team}}\n{{1997 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n{{1998 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n{{1999 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n{{1995 AFL pre-season draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Matthew}}\n[[Category:Essendon Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Coleman Medal winners]]\n[[Category:All-Australians (AFL)]]\n[[Category:Victorian State of Origin players]]\n[[Category:Champions of Essendon]]\n[[Category:People educated at St. Bernard's College, Melbourne]]\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Western Jets players]]\n[[Category:Australian Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Australia international rules football team players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian rules footballer}}\n{{For|other people with the same name|Matthew Lloyd (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Matthew Lloyd\n| image = Matthew Lloyd 2005.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Lloyd in 2005\n| fullname = Matthew James Lloyd\n| nickname = Lloydy, Velvet Sledgehammer, Sniper <ref>http://www.couriermail.com.au/sport/afl/the-end-hit-lloydy-with-thud/story-e6frepf6-1225778920861</ref><ref>http://www.heraldsun.com.au/afl/teams/lay-off-lloydy/story-e6frf9l6-1111116596784</ref> Lordo<ref>{{cite tweet|user=MatthewLloyd18|author=Matthew Lloyd|number=326316171345424384|date=22 April 2013|title=\u201c@JakeBourke: @stevesmithffx @crammj @matthewlloyd18 It's actually 'Lordo', folks. No idea why. Billy accidentally called me that, it stuck}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|4|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| originalteam = [[Western Jets]] ([[TAC Cup]])\n| draftpick = [[1994 AFL Draft|1995 Pre-Season Draft]]\n| height = 192 cm\n| weight = 92 kg\n| position = [[Full-forward]]\n| statsend = 2009\n| years1 = 1995\u20132009\n| club1 = {{AFL Ess}}\n| games_goals1 = 270 (926)\n| sooyears1 = 1997\u20131999\n| sooteam1 = [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]]\n| soogames_goals1 = 3  (8)\n| nationalyears1 = 2001\n| nationalteam1 = [[Australian International rules football team|Australia]]\n| nationalgames_goals1 = 2 (4)\n| careerhighlights = *3\u00d7 [[Coleman Medal]]: 2000, 2001, 2003 \n*12\u00d7 [[List of Essendon Football Club leading goalkickers|Essendon leading goalkicker]]: 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2007, 2008, 2009  \n*5\u00d7 [[All-Australian Team|All-Australian team]]: 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003\n*[[Australian Football League|AFL]] premiership: [[2000 AFL Grand Final|2000]] \n*[[Goal of the Year (Australia)|Goal of the Year]]: 2007\n*[[Mark of the Year]]: 2008\n*[[List of Essendon Football Club captains|Essendon Captain]]: 2006\u20132009\n*[[Jim Stynes Medal]]: 2001\n*[[AFL Rising Star]] nominee: [[1996 AFL Rising Star|1996]]\n*[[Essendon Football Club|Champions of Essendon]]: No. 22\n*[[Australian Football Hall of Fame]]\n}}\n\n'''Matthew James Lloyd''' (born 16 April 1978) is a former professional [[Australian rules football]]er, who played for the [[Essendon Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL).\n\nA highly decorated [[full-forward]], Lloyd's AFL's honours include being the eighth all time [https://afltables.com/afl/stats/biglists/bg1.txt leading goalkicker] in the history of AFL, [[List of VFL/AFL players to have scored 500 goals|eighth-highest]], with  three [[Coleman Medal]]s as leading goalkicker in the league, AFL life membership, as well as winning both the [[Mark of the Year]] and [[Goal of the Year (Australia)|Goal of the Year]] awards.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=7213 |title=Lloyd to be inducted as AFL life Member |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=5393 |title=Lloyd Awarded Goal Of The Year |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date=2007-09-26 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107103405/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=5393 |archive-date=7 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=6120 |title=Lloyd Wins Mark Of The Year |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106201958/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=6120 |archive-date=6 January 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Among his representative honours are five [[All-Australian]] selections, three times representing the [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria State of Origin team]], as well as twice representing Australia in [[International rules football]].\n\nLloyd has kicked over 100 goals in a season \u2013 twice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/th-goal-sparks-reunion/story-e6frf9jf-1111117178695 |title=Bomber Matthew Lloyd Recalls Reunions Amid Crush |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> He also belongs to the small group of players whose [[First kick \u2013 first goal (Australian rules football)|first kick in the AFL resulted in a goal]].\n\n==Early life==\nMatthew Lloyd was born in Melbourne in 1978 to parents [[John Lloyd (Australian footballer)|John]] (a former VFL footballer who played 29 games for the [[Carlton Football Club]] from 1965\u20131967) and Bev Lloyd. The Lloyds moved to Scotland for three years because of John's work, and it was there that Matthew picked up [[rugby football|rugby]] and [[soccer]] playing for his [[Currie]] club.\n\nLloyd attended St Martin De Porres Parish Primary School in [[Avondale Heights]] before moving to [[St. Bernard's College, Melbourne]].<ref>[http://sbc.melb.catholic.edu.au/groups/oc/wof.html St Bernard's Old Collegians Wall of Fame]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nHe supported the [[Fitzroy Football Club]] when he was young because in the first game he attended, Fitzroy player [[Bernie Quinlan]] kicked nine goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/tabid/208/default.aspx?newsid=37730 |title=Unforgettable time for Lloyd |publisher=Afl.com.au |date=2007-02-08 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===AFL===\nLloyd was drafted into the AFL as a 16-year-old in the [[1994 AFL Draft|1995 Pre-season Draft]] as a \"compensatory selection\" that was awarded to Essendon by the AFL in return for losing [[Todd Ridley]] to the newly formed [[Fremantle Football Club]]. The Bombers picked up what would be one of their all-time greats for a relative pittance in the draft. Lloyd was heralded as a future football star after his AFL debut in Round 14, 1995, where he scored a goal with his first kick in league football and three for the match.\n\nThe key features of Lloyd's game were his powerful [[Mark (Australian football)|mark]]s on the lead (particularly overhead), his use of his body in a defensive capacity and accurate goal kicking, particularly from [[set shot]]s on his left foot. He converted a large majority of set shots inside the [[50-metre arc]] and kicked further than 50 metres on a regular basis.\n\nLloyd was known for his ritual when taking set shots at goal. Almost every time, he took time to go far back on the mark, pull both his socks up, and then grab some grass and throw it into the air to measure the wind and take a very long run-up before kicking. In 2006, the AFL introduced a \"shot clock\" to limit the amount of time that players had to take set shots; although Lloyd's ritual was not the longest in the league, its quirks made it so well known that the rule became commonly known as the \"Lloyd Rule\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/afl/lloyd-rule-to-speed-up-goalkicking/2005/11/25/1132703381229.html |title=Lloyd Rule to speed up goalkicking |publisher=Smh.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> Lloyd adjusted his ritual to fit into the new rule, and he still retained the most famous aspect (throwing grass) until the end of his career.\n\nLloyd's goal-scoring ability enabled him to top the Essendon goal scoring every year from 1997 to 2009, except for 2006 when he only played three games due to a serious hamstring injury.\n\n[[File:Matthew lloyd.jpg|220px|thumb|Lloyd in the 2007 AFL season]]\n\nLloyd was selected in the [[All-Australian team]] on five occasions (1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003), won the [[Coleman Medal]] for kicking the most goals in the regular season three times (2000, 2001 and 2003)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afl.com.au/aflhq/awards/colemanmedal/previouswinners/tabid/15089/default.aspx |title=Coleman Medal - Previous Winners |publisher=Afl.com.au |date=2012-01-04 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120924113126/http://www.afl.com.au/aflhq/awards/colemanmedal/previouswinners/tabid/15089/default.aspx |archivedate=24 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and twice kicked more than 100 goals in a completed season (109 in 2000 and 105 in 2001; on both occasions he reached the milestone during the finals).\n\nLloyd was a member of Essendon's 2000 [[List of Australian Football League premiers|premiership]] team and was captain of Essendon from 2006 to 2009. He was recognised for his achievements at Essendon in 2002 when he was ranked the 22nd greatest player ever to play for the club in the \"[[Champions of Essendon]]\" list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/champions/ |title=Champions of Essendon |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |accessdate=2012-09-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812032019/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/champions/ |archivedate=12 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nLloyd was appointed Essendon captain ahead of the 2006 season after [[James Hird]] elected to stand down following the side's disappointing [[2005 AFL season|2005 season]].<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2005-09-27/lloyd-to-lead-bombers/2112816 Lloyd to lead Bombers - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)]</ref> Lloyd's first match as Essendon captain resulted in a 27-point win over the defending premiers [[Sydney Swans|Sydney]], where he kicked eight goals (six of them in the first quarter alone). It would be the only win that Essendon would enjoy under Lloyd's captaincy until exactly a year later.<ref name=\"BombersvSwans2006\">[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-04-01/bombers-upset-swans/1721794 Bombers upset Swans - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)]</ref>\n\nAs well as being the top all-time goal scorer,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=2777 |title=A Record Breaking Performance |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date=2003-08-10 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050103162750/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=2777 |archive-date=3 January 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> captain<ref>{{cite news | url =http://newsstore.fairfax.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=nstore&docID=AGE050928HT6P05963JH | title =Lloyd tips a new era for Bombers| first = Len| last = Johnson |date=28 September 2005| work =The Age}}</ref> and life member<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4020 |title=Lloyd A Life Member |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date=2004-12-17 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050717103921/http://essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4020 |archive-date=17 July 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> at Essendon, Lloyd was part of its 2000 premiership team.\n\nIn 2013, Lloyd was inducted as a member of the [[Australian Football Hall of Fame]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/afl/essendon-champion-matthew-lloyd-joins-afl-elite/story-fndv8gad-1226657195651 |title=Lloyd joins AFL elite |publisher=news.com.au |date=2013-06-05 |accessdate=2013-06-05}}</ref> and as a Legend in the Essendon Football Club Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/2013-03-04/greats-honoured |title=Essendon greats honoured |publisher=essendonfc.com.au |date=2013-03-04 |accessdate=2013-06-05}}</ref>\n\n===State of Origin===\nLloyd had a successful [[Interstate matches in Australian rules football|State of Origin]] career, kicking 8 goals in 3 games. He first played for [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]] in 1997, against [[South Australia Australian rules football team|South Australia]], kicking 3 goals, including a [[snap kick]] along the ground from near the boundary line, which went one way then curved back another.<ref>{{Citation|last=Costa Sports|title=That Was the Season That Was 1997 AFL|date=2015-04-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qI5OoBus5dw|accessdate=2016-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Costa Sports|title=That Was the Season That Was 1997 AFL|date=2015-04-18|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qI5OoBus5dw|accessdate=2016-03-31}}</ref> In 1998 Lloyd kicked two goals against [[The Allies (Australian rules football)|The Allies]], in Brisbane. Lloyd last played for Victoria in 1999 against South Australia in the second-last ever State of Origin game, kicking 3 goals and being named in the best players.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cedric.slv.vic.gov.au/view/action/nmets.do?DOCCHOICE=2192339.xml&dvs=1459417201184~655&locale=en_AU&search_terms=&adjacency=&VIEWER_URL=/view/action/nmets.do?&DELIVERY_RULE_ID=4&divType=&usePid1=true&usePid2=true|title=Digitised Resource Viewer|website=cedric.slv.vic.gov.au|access-date=2016-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Career highlights==\nIn Round 20 2007 Lloyd kicked a backheel goal whilst surrounded by opponents and was awarded the ''2007 Goal of the Year''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/best-goal-mark-of-the-year-announced/story-e6frg7mx-1111114508240 |title=Best goal and mark of the year announced |publisher=Theaustralian.com.au |date=2012-02-17 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nIn Round 18 against the [[Melbourne Football Club|Melbourne Demons]], Lloyd took a spectacular mark above five players to win the ''2008 Mark of the Year''. A haul of eight goals in that match gave Lloyd his best return since Round 1, 2006.\n\n===Performances against the Sydney Swans===\nIn Round 3, 1999, Lloyd, aged just 21 at the time, kicked a record 13 goals against the [[Sydney Swans]] at the MCG, kicking the first goal of the game and breaking [[John Coleman (Australian footballer)|John Coleman]]'s record for most goals kicked by an Essendon player against the Swans.<ref name=\"sevenmoments\">[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/seven-controversial-moments-in-career-of-essendon-champ-and-hall-of-fame-inductee-matthew-lloyd/story-fni5f6kv-1226657827182 Seven controversial moments of Essendon champ and Hall of Fame inductee Matthew Lloyd], ''Herald Sun'', 5 June 2013</ref>\n\nIn his first game as Essendon captain, also playing against the Sydney Swans, Lloyd kicked eight goals (six in the first quarter against his opponent, [[Leo Barry]])<ref name=\"BombersvSwans2006\"/><ref name=\"sevenmoments\"/> He kicked a total of 69 goals playing against the Swans, including the aforementioned 13 in 1999 and eight in the first round of the 2006 season.<ref name=\"playerstats\">[http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/M/Matthew_Lloyd0.html Matthew Lloyd], ''AFL Tables''</ref>\n\n==Injuries==\nDuring Essendon's 1996 preliminary final against the [[Sydney Swans]] in Sydney, Lloyd ruptured his spleen in the second quarter. He suffered a large amount of blood loss and spent 10 days in intensive care in a Sydney hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/caring-dons-laud-dedicated-docs/story-0-1111117210036 |title=Caring Dons laud dedicated docs |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theage.com.au/sport/afl/i-would-ve-died-that-night-lloyd-s-other-1996-prelim-nightmare-20200326-p54e9l.html?fbclid=IwAR12iA7YnA1vt7YjUKoVs2Z_2Qwb8-b6DgIQNhlbWdjX3gEko8sKiQMb8Ps|title='I would\u2019ve died that night': Lloyd's other 1996 prelim nightmare|publisher=The Age|first=Ronny|last=Lerner|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn Round 6, 2002 against [[Fremantle Football Club|Fremantle]], Lloyd ruptured a tendon in his right ring finger when it was caught in his opponents guernsey. It required surgery to be reattached and he was out for eight weeks.\n\nLloyd returned in Round 14 against the [[Western Bulldogs]] when [[Steven Kretiuk]] controversially targeted his injured hand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/07/07/1025667089931.html |title=Review on Kretiuk incident |publisher=Theage.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nMidway through the third quarter of the Essendon vs [[Western Bulldogs|Bulldogs]] match on 16 April 2006 (which happened to be Lloyd's 28th birthday), opponent [[Brian Lake|Brian Harris]] accidentally fell on Lloyd as he tried to mark the ball. Lloyd walked off the ground with the aid of trainers and did not return for the rest of the match. Following scans, a week later it was revealed that the hamstring tendon had been snapped off the bone. Surgery to repair the career-threatening injury took place which ruled him out for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4662 |title=Lloyd Injury Shock |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date=2006-04-22 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070816043530/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4662 |archive-date=16 August 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2006/04/23/1621921.htm |title=Lloyd Shattered By Hamstring Injury |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=2006-04-23 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> Lloyd's absence from the team was felt hard, as the Bombers finished near the foot of the ladder at season's end. As Lloyd was captain of Essendon and was unable to play for the remainder of the season (his first year in fact), [[David Hille]] was promoted to team captain in Lloyd's absence.\n\nLloyd made a successful comeback against [[Adelaide Football Club|Adelaide]] at [[AAMI Stadium]] in Round 1, 2007. He kicked two goals while working further up the ground, putting to rest any concerns about his injured hamstring. Essendon beat Adelaide by 31 points.\n\n==Brad Sewell incident==\nIn Round 22, 2009, Lloyd ended {{AFL Haw}}'s finals hopes (and their premiership defence) when he hit [[Brad Sewell]] with a heavy bump that left him unconscious and with facial injuries, and it led to a brawl between the two teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/matthew-lloyd-bump-fires-up-essendon/story-e6frfb9x-1225767349823 |title=Matthew Lloyd bump fires up Essendon |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=714jxXF7LLc |title=Matthew Lloyd clashes with Brad Sewell footage |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-08-29 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> In the bitter aftermath of the match, Hawthorn's [[Campbell Brown (footballer)|Campbell Brown]] called Lloyd \"one of the biggest snipers in the game\" and said that \"his time is coming\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Barrett |first=Damian |url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/afl-premiership/campbell-brown-says-matthew-lloyd-is-one-of-the-biggest-snipers-in-the-game/story-e6frf3e3-1225767452130 |title=Brown Slams Lloyd The 'Sniper' |publisher=Foxsports.com.au |date=2009-08-30 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> Hawthorn coach [[Alastair Clarkson]] threatened Lloyd and abused an interchange steward and had to be restrained by Hawthorn football manager Mark Evans as the teams left the field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/what-hawthorns-alastair-clarkson-really-said-to-essendons-matthew-lloyd/story-e6frf9jf-1225769304064 |title=What Clarkson Said To Lloyd |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> AFL CEO [[Andrew Demetriou]] defended Lloyd's reputation,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/sport/afl/afl-finals-matthew-lloyd-no-sniper-andrew-demetriou/story-e6freck3-1225768274699 |title=Matthew Lloyd No Sniper |publisher=Adelaidenow.com.au |date=2009-09-01 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> Clarkson was fined for his comments<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/alastair-clarkson-fined-for-matthew-lloyd-spray/story-e6frf9jf-1225769275418 |title=Alastair Clarkson fined for Matthew Lloyd comments |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> and later apologised for the outburst.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/sport/a/-/afl/5898826/clarkson-sorry-for-post-match-outburst/ |title=Clarkson sorry for post-match outburst |publisher=Au.news.yahoo.com |date=2009-08-31 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nEssendon went on to win the match by 17 points after trailing by 22 points at the time of the incident, and in the week after the match, Lloyd was given a six-match suspension by the match review panel for the hit on Sewell. This was reduced to four matches after he decided not to appeal the sanction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/afl-finals-matthew-lloyd-bombers-accept-penalties/story-e6frf9jf-1225768125484 |title=Lloyd, Bombers accept penalties |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> Lloyd only served one match of his suspension, Essendon's elimination final loss to {{AFL Ade}} at [[Football Park|AAMI Stadium]], before announcing his retirement on 23 September 2009.\n\n==Statistics==\n:<ref>http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/M/Matthew_Lloyd0.html</ref>\n\n{{AFL player statistics legend}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|style=\"background:#CFECEC; width:1em\"|\n|Led the league for the season only\n|-\n|style=\"background:#b7e718; width:1em\"|\n|Led the league after finals only\n|-\n|style=\"background:#DD6E81; width:1em\"|\n|Led the league after season and finals\n|}\n\n{{AFL player statistics start}}\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1995 AFL season|1995]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Ess}}\n| 18 || 5 || 7 || 6 || 31 || 17 || 48 || 22 || 1 || 1.4 || 1.2 || 6.2 || 3.4 || 9.6 || 4.4 || 0.2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1996 AFL season|1996]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Ess}}\n| 18 || 11 || 18 || 7 || 78 || 34 || 112 || 46 || 11 || 1.6 || 0.6 || 7.1 || 3.1 || 10.2 || 4.2 || 1.0\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1997 AFL season|1997]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Ess}}\n| 18 || 20 || 63 || 33 || 212 || 125 || 272 || 125 || 17 || 3.2 || 1.7 || 10.6 || 3.0 || 13.6 || 6.3 || 0.9\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1998 AFL season|1998]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Ess}}\n| 18 || 23 || 70 || 38 || 249 || 77 || 326 || 156 || 24 || 3.0 || 1.7 || 10.8 || 3.3 || 14.2 || 6.8 || 1.0\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1999 AFL season|1999]]\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{AFL Ess}}\n| 18 || 22 || 87 || 40 || 239 || 54 || 293 || 142 || 22 || 4.0 || 1.8 || 10.9 || 2.5 || 13.3 || 6.5 || 1.0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2000 AFL season|2000]]\n|st