2000\n**'''[[McClelland Trophy]] ([[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]])''': 1999, 2000, 2001\n**'''[[Australian Football League pre-season competition|Pre-Season Cup]] ([[Essendon Football Club|Essendon]])''': 2000\n*'''Individual'''\n**'''[[Coleman Medal]]''': 2000, 2001, 2003\n**'''[[All-Australian team|All-Australian]]''': 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2003\n**'''[[List of Essendon Football Club leading goalkickers|Essendon F.C. Leading Goalkicker]]''': 1997, 1998, 1999, 2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004, 2005, 2007, 2008, 2009\n**'''[[List of Essendon Football Club captains|Essendon F.C. Captain]]''': 2006-2009\n**'''[[Australian international rules football team|Australian Representative Honours in]] [[International rules football|International Rules Football]]''': 2001\n**'''[[International Rules Series#Jim Stynes Medal|Jim Stynes Medal]]''': 2001\n**'''[[Goal of the Year (AFL)|Goal of the Year]]''': 2007\n**'''[[Mark of the Year|Alex Jesaulenko Medal - Mark of the Year]]''': 2008\n**'''[[AFL Rising Star|AFL Rising Star Nominee]]''': 1996 (Round 19)\n**'''[[Essendon Football Club#Champions of Essendon|Champions of Essendon - No. 22]]'''\n**'''[[Australian Football Hall of Fame]] inductee'''\n\n==Retirement==\nOn 23 September 2009, Lloyd announced his retirement to a packed media conference at the Essendon Football Club Hall of Fame. Although he had been offered another contract,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=7035 |title=Lloyd requests more time |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923004305/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=7035 |archive-date=23 September 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Lloyd said that \"now is my time from a physical and mental point of view\" and that he would \"...prefer to go a year too early than a year too late.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afl.com.au/news/newsarticle/tabid/208/newsid/85180/default.aspx |title=Lloyd quits |publisher=Afl.com.au |date=2009-09-23 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nTo celebrate Lloyd's career, the Coventry End of [[Docklands Stadium]] is renamed the Lloyd End for Essendon home games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/honour-a-fitting-end-for-matthew-lloyd/story-e6frf9jf-1225809744183 |title=Honour a fitting end for Matthew Lloyd |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Lloyd was appointed assistant coach at the AIS-AFL Academy<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ausport.gov.au/ais/sports/australian_football/news/afl_stars_lloyd_and_oloughlin_lend_support_to_emerging_talent |title=Lloyd and O'Loughlin Lend Support To Emerging Talent |publisher=Ausport.gov.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110330165928/http://www.ausport.gov.au/ais/sports/australian_football/news/afl_stars_lloyd_and_oloughlin_lend_support_to_emerging_talent |archive-date=30 March 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> however he ruled out applying for an AFL coaching position.<ref>http://www.theadvocate.com.au/news/local/sport/football-australian-rules/lloyds-coaching-aspirations-on-hold/2370200.aspx</ref>\n\n==Media work==\nLloyd co-hosted children's AFL show ''Auskick'n Around'' on [[Fox Footy Channel]] with [[Brad Johnson (Australian footballer)|Brad Johnson]] from the [[Western Bulldogs]] from 2003 until it was cancelled at the end of 2005.\n\nIn 2006 Lloyd had a weekly spot as a panelist on [[Fox Footy]]'s ''White Line Fever'' and after being forced to spend extended time off the field because of injury, he became recognised for his informative views on all things football \u2013 his roles included being a [[special comments]] commentator on [[Triple M]]'s football coverage as well as more regular appearances on ''[[The AFL Footy Show]]'', as a panelist.\n\nIn 2009 Lloyd appeared as a regular panelist on a new show, ''[[One Week at a Time (AFL)|One Week at a Time]]'', as well as doing special comments on [[Network Ten]] and writing a regular column for  ''[[The Age]]'' newspaper. Following his retirement Lloyd has been heavily involved in the media.\n\nLloyd signed with the Network Ten<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onehd.com.au/shows-matthew-lloyd.htm| title = OneHD: Matthew Lloyd profile| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110723224346/http://one.com.au/shows-matthew-lloyd.htm | archivedate=23 July 2011}}</ref> AFL team as an expert commentator for the [[2010 AFL season|2010]] and 2011 AFL seasons on Channel Ten and [[10 Bold|One HD]] (he had already provided special commentary during various matches of the [[2009 AFL season]] for the network), until [[Ten Sport]] lost the rights at the end of the [[2011 AFL season]]. He also worked for radio station [[SEN 1116|SEN]], was a co-host of ''[[The Game Plan (Australian TV series)|The Game Plan]]'' on One HD during 2011 and continued working for ''The Age''.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/afl/by/matthew-lloyd The Age: Matthew Lloyd]</ref>\n\nLloyd's autobiography (co-authored with Andrew Clarke), ''Straight Shooter'', was released in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/matthew-lloyds-final-stand-for-the-bombers/story-e6frf9jf-1226098631937 |title=Lloyd's Final Stand For The Bombers |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/a-fear-of-failure-was-my-greatest-spur-from-the-very-start-20110720-1howe.html |title=A fear of failure was my greatest spur from the very start |publisher=Theage.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nAfter Network Ten lost the AFL broadcasting rights, Lloyd joined the [[Nine Network]] for 2012 to be a panelist on ''[[The Footy Show (AFL)|The Footy Show]]'' and ''[[The Footy Show (AFL)|The Sunday Footy Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/tv-radio/channel-9-signs-matthew-lloyd/story-e6frf9ho-1226171130199 |title=Channel 9 signs Matthew Lloyd |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> He also left SEN to join [[3AW]]'s AFL special comments team.\n\nIn 2013, he joined ''[[Footy Classified]]'' as a panelist alongside [[Gary Lyon]], [[Craig Hutchison (broadcaster)|Craig Hutchison]] and [[Caroline Wilson]]; as well as continuing his regular roles on ''The Sunday Footy Show'' and 3AW Football. Lloyd is also a recurring panelist on ''The Footy Show'' and on occasion appears on ''[[Nine News Melbourne]]'' to provide insights into the weekly round of matches.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=9NewsMelb |number=1045595844425072641 |date=28 September 2018 |title=Tomorrow's Grand Final tips with @MatthewLloyd18. Who will win? #9News }}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nOn 14 November 2014 it was announced that Lloyd would return to the Essendon Football Club as a part-time forwards coach, working closely with the club's forwards.<ref>[http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/2014-11-14/lloyd-back-in Lloyd Back In for 2015], Essendon Football Club official website, 14 November 2014</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLloyd's parents are [[John Lloyd (Australian footballer)|John]] and Bev Lloyd. John Lloyd played 29 games for [[Carlton Football Club|Carlton]] from 1965\u20131967 and coached the Braybrook Football Club to three premierships. The family moved to Scotland for three years because of John Lloyd's work and it was there that Lloyd played [[rugby football|rugby]] and [[soccer]] for his [[Currie]] club.\n\nLloyd has two older brothers, Simon, who is an assistant coach at the [[Geelong Football Club]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fremantlefc.com.au/news/newsarticle/tabid/7009/newsid/104367/default.aspx |title=Assistant coaching role for Simon Lloyd |publisher=Fremantlefc.com.au |date=2010-10-22 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110302075336/http://www.fremantlefc.com.au/news/newsarticle/tabid/7009/newsid/104367/default.aspx |archive-date=2 March 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Brad Lloyd|Brad]], who is  a former [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]] player (and former captain of the [[Williamstown Football Club]]) and now head of football at the [[Carlton Football Club]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fremantlefc.com.au/Default.aspx?tabid=7009&newsId=55446 |title=National Recruiting Manager appointed |publisher=Fremantlefc.com.au |date=2008-02-20 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706104827/http://www.fremantlefc.com.au/Default.aspx?tabid=7009&newsId=55446 |archivedate=6 July 2011 }}</ref> as well as one older sister, Kylie, who is the Unit Manager at ''[[The AFL Footy Show|The Footy Show]]''.\n\nOn 9 November 2002, Lloyd married his childhood sweetheart, Lisa-Marie Caparello, usually known as \"Lisa\", at [[Xavier College (Melbourne)|Xavier College]] Chapel. Their wedding was covered by ''New Idea'' magazine and a documentary of the day, titled ''One Day In November'', was also aired on [[Fox Footy]] Channel. \nLisa Lloyd appeared on [[The Footy Show (AFL)|The Footy Show]]'s singing competition, ''Screamers'', in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4209 |title=Support our latest Bomber star |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date=2005-04-28 |accessdate=2012-09-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050619023559/http://essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4209 |archive-date=19 June 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and was also a regular presenter on [[Fox Footy]]'s ''Living With Footballers''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/03/31/1080544543170.html |title=Living With Footballers |publisher=The Age |date=2004-04-01 |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Lloyds have three children; Jaeda Ruby (born December 2006),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/news.asp?nid=4978 |title=Lloyd Family Grows By One |publisher=Essendonfc.com.au |date=2006-12-16 |accessdate=2012-09-25 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Kira Grace (born September 2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/another-baby-girl-for-lloyd/story-e6frf7jo-1225769757156 |title=Another baby girl for Lloyd |publisher=Heraldsun.com.au |date= |accessdate=2012-09-25}}</ref> and Jacob Matthew (born November 2012).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/a/Lloyd-family-welcomes-baby-boy/10227 |title=Lloyd family welcomes baby boy |publisher=Essendon footy Club |date= |accessdate=2012-11-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121130214636/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/news/a/Lloyd-family-welcomes-baby-boy/10227 |archive-date=30 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book| first=Matthew |last=Lloyd | year=2011 |publisher=Random House Australia |isbn= 978-1-86471-293-3 |title=Matthew Lloyd: Straight Shooter}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Essplayer|ref=13223}}\n*{{AFL Tables|ref=M/Matthew_Lloyd0.html}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110226171645/http://www.essendonfc.com.au/team/player-past.asp?id=542#profile Essendon Past Players Profile: Matthew Lloyd]\n\n{{AFL Coleman Medallists}}\n{{2000 Essendon premiership players}}\n{{Essendon Football Club captains}}\n{{Essendon leading goalkickers}}\n{{1998 All-Australian team}}\n{{1999 All-Australian team}}\n{{2000 All-Australian team}}\n{{2001 All-Australian team}}\n{{2003 All-Australian team}}\n{{Alex Jesaulenko Medal}}\n{{Goal of the Year}}\n{{1996 AFL Rising Star nominees}}\n{{Jim Stynes Medal}}\n{{1998 Australian international rules team}}\n{{2001 Australian international rules team}}\n{{1997 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n{{1998 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n{{1999 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n{{1995 AFL pre-season draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd, Matthew}}\n[[Category:Essendon Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Coleman Medal winners]]\n[[Category:All-Australians (AFL)]]\n[[Category:Victorian State o